every element belongs to the clustering with its closest centroid (mean element)

* ε is the radious of a neighborhood
* the density is the number of points
* a point is said to be a core point
if it has more than minPoints within ε
* a point is said to be a border point
if it has less than minPoints within ε,
but it is in the neighborhood of core point
* a noise point is any point that is not
a core point or a border point
* the core points and their kth nearest neighbors are approximately
at the same distance (and close to each others)
* the noise points have their k-th nearest neighbors far away
Therefore, we can sort based on the distance between their kth NNs.

Separation measures how well-separated is a cluster from the others
